SIMPLE: recreate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Recreate
<hw>Rec"re*ate</hw> <pr>(rk"r*t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Recreated</conjf>
<pr>(-`td)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Recreating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>recreatus</ets>, p.
p. of <ets>recreate</ets> to create anew, to refresh; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>creare</ets> to create. See
<er>Create</er>.]</ety> <def>To give fresh life to; to reanimate; to
revive; especially, to refresh after wearying toil or anxiety; to
relieve; to cheer; to divert; to amuse; to gratify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Painters, when they work on white grounds, place before them
colors mixed with blue and green, to <qex>recreate</qex> their eyes,
white wearying . . . the sight more than any.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>St. John, who <qex>recreated</qex> himself with sporting with a
tame partridge.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These ripe fruits <qex>recreate</qex> the nostrils with their
aromatic scent.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recreate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Recreate
<hw>Rec"re*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To take recreation.</def>
<rj><au>L. Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recreation</ent>⟦br⟧
